name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @DoctorVive I don't know. I'm a pilot. I wouldn't want to be caught on bad weather and put on a hold for an hr. There is a reason for nbaa reserves. It's a necessary margin of safety. Unexpected things happen when you fly.

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @DoctorVive 3/ do you know how many wh/km does @EviationAero uses in average for 1000km? (not just cruise)

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @DoctorVive 2/ assuming nbaa like reserves you'd need 1500km of storage per 1000km of flight. What's the wh/km efficiency of an e-jet. If the math works despite throwing away the pack then Li-S or Li Metal possible. Otherwise it's Li Ion but range is limited to regional

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @DoctorVive @EviationAero You may be right

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @DoctorVive 1/ how many wh/km for e-jet? Never ran the math on cost of fuel at $4/gal for 300 1000km flights vs a new high energy density pack overhaul at $0.3/wh/300 flights. Regional jet fuel est at 200gph (400gallons per 1000km) or $1600 ($480k fuel fuel/300 legs).

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @DoctorVive @EviationAero Definitely a tech demo possible but the packs would last 6mo. Before we had Tesla we had 15yrs of Prius. It paved the way. My money is on hybridization before full EV to mature components and give time for batteries to catch up to long range.

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @DoctorVive @EviationAero And even then you are fighting with nature. Maybe you have data I haven't seen. Willing to be convinced but have not seen proof Li Metal or LiS will ever meet the requirements beyond a demo flight.

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @DoctorVive @EviationAero I'd love LiS or Li Metal to be real but they are well over a decade away. This I have a good handle on.

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @DoctorVive You won't find a bigger advocate for electric drive than me but it's not possible to go there in under a decade. Before we have e-jets we will have turboelectric propulsion (higher efficiency). That means liquid H2 or a clean carbon neutral fuel.

text: @Robotbeat @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC Tell me more about the electric motor you are designing. How many MW? How many lb of thrust?

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC What planes have you designed? Any of them carry passengers? Passenger planes fly above M0.8, need to fit airport gates, etc. Otherwise we'd all be jetting in drela wings, that stuff is impractical.

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC What is 0.6? I'm not sure I understand how you are calculating this. Where is the efficiency of the power train? The weight of the structure? The weight of the power electronics. Airplanes climb, cruise and descend...that's not a model

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC A 787 is L/D about 20. This is where the math doesn't work...if you want to do a solar impulse like demo or a 2 passenger trainer then fine but if you want to carry passengers electric without onboard generation is totally practical with 2019 technology

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC You'd never get FAA type certification if your battery stops working below 0C. I certified a battery with FAA. The Cessna CJ4 battery was designed by my old co and that wasn't even the fuel source

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC I don't buy it. Send me the math. DM open

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC 2/ The two chemistries you mention will never be flight practical. They don't work at low temp. It's -60 at ISA at 41000ft. They have terrible cycle life. They have terrible calendar life. Lithium metal is not safe at those battery sizes

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @Robotbeat @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC 1/ Chris, this is where we start to swim in bullshit. What's the useful load of a 600m range full electric plane? Is it a passenger carrying airframe? One thing is a demo or a 2 person trainer and another a real product

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC 3/ for electric power train aviation to be practical we need turbo electric generation onboard. There are architectures like I described above that would beat the efficiency/thrust/range of even today's best jet engines.

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC 2/ batteries on all electric planes with Lithoum Ion work only for small range propeller systems (under 200 mi range). The FAA/NBAA reserve rules are 100mi remaining at landing so your effective range would be only 100mi. It's super niche.

name: Ric Fulop ðŸš€
text: @mattocko @AlexanderGirau @advano @ntopologyinc @RescaleInc @DesktopMetal @DCVC 1/ unfortunately it's not even close. Solar doesn't even work in a car, how will it work on a plane? It's negative for all passenger carrying aero structures. Only makes sense in impractical demos like solar impulse or high altitude persistent drones.
